content.brief: The human readable file name of the artifact, typically generated during build and release processes. Often includes the package name and version in the file name.

content.name: artifact.version
content.brief: The version of the artifact.

content.name: artifact.purl
content.brief: The [Package URL](https://github.com/package-url/purl-spec) of the [package artifact](https://slsa.dev/spec/v1.0/terminology#package-model) provides a standard way to identify and locate the packaged artifact.

content.name: artifact.hash
content.brief: The full [hash value (see glossary)](https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/FIPS/NIST.FIPS.186-5.pdf), often found in checksum.txt on a release of the artifact and used to verify package integrity.

content.name: artifact.attestation.id
content.brief: The id of the build [software attestation](https://slsa.dev/attestation-model).

content.name: artifact.attestation.filename
content.brief: The provenance filename of the built attestation which directly relates to the build artifact filename. This filename SHOULD accompany the artifact at publish time. See the [SLSA Relationship](https://slsa.dev/spec/v1.0/distributing-provenance#relationship-between-artifacts-and-attestations) specification for more information.

content.name: artifact.attestation.hash
content.brief: The full [hash value (see glossary)](https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/FIPS/NIST.FIPS.186-5.pdf), of the built attestation. Some envelopes in the [software attestation space](https://github.com/in-toto/attestation/tree/main/spec) also refer to this as the **digest**.

content.name: container.name
content.brief: Container name used by container runtime.

content.name: container.id
content.brief: Container ID. Usually a UUID, as for example used to [identify Docker containers](https://docs.docker.com/engine/containers/run/#container-identification). The UUID might be abbreviated.

content.name: container.runtime
content.brief: The container runtime managing this container.

content.name: container.image.name
content.brief: Name of the image the container was built on.

content.name: container.image.tags
content.brief: Container image tags. An example can be found in [Docker Image Inspect](https://docs.docker.com/engine/api/v1.43/#tag/Image/operation/ImageInspect). Should be only the `<tag>` section of the full name for example from `registry.example.com/my-org/my-image:<tag>`.

content.name: container.image.id
content.brief: Runtime specific image identifier. Usually a hash algorithm followed by a UUID.

content.name: container.image.repo_digests
content.brief: Repo digests of the container image as provided by the container runtime.

content.name: container.command
content.brief: The command used to run the container (i.e. the command name).

content.name: container.command_line
content.brief: The full command run by the container as a single string representing the full command.

content.name: container.command_args
content.brief: All the command arguments (including the command/executable itself) run by the container.

content.name: container.label
content.brief: Container labels, `<key>` being the label name, the value being the label value.

content.name: container.csi.plugin.name
content.brief: The name of the CSI ([Container Storage Interface](https://github.com/container-storage-interface/spec)) plugin used by the volume.

content.name: container.csi.volume.id
content.brief: The unique volume ID returned by the CSI ([Container Storage Interface](https://github.com/container-storage-interface/spec)) plugin.

content.name: source.address
content.brief: Source address - domain name if available without reverse DNS lookup; otherwise, IP address or Unix domain socket name.

content.name: source.port
content.brief: Source port number

content.name: cpu.mode
content.brief: The mode of the CPU

content.name: code.function.name
content.brief: The method or function name, or equivalent (usually rightmost part of the code unit's name).

content.name: code.namespace
content.brief: The "namespace" within which `code.function.name` is defined. Usually the qualified class or module name, such that `code.namespace` + some separator + `code.function.name` form a unique identifier for the code unit.

content.name: code.file.path
content.brief: The source code file name that identifies the code unit as uniquely as possible (preferably an absolute file path).

content.name: code.line.number
content.brief: The line number in `code.file.path` best representing the operation. It SHOULD point within the code unit named in `code.function.name`.

content.name: code.column.number
content.brief: The column number in `code.file.path` best representing the operation. It SHOULD point within the code unit named in `code.function.name`.

content.name: code.stacktrace
content.brief: A stacktrace as a string in the natural representation for the language runtime. The representation is to be determined and documented by each language SIG.

content.name: graphql.operation.name
content.brief: The name of the operation being executed.

content.name: graphql.operation.type
content.brief: The type of the operation being executed.

content.name: graphql.document
content.brief: The GraphQL document being executed.

content.name: session.id
content.brief: A unique id to identify a session.

content.name: session.previous_id
content.brief: The previous `session.id` for this user, when known.

content.name: v8js.gc.type
content.brief: The type of garbage collection.

content.name: v8js.heap.space.name
content.brief: The name of the space type of heap memory.

content.name: cicd.pipeline.name
content.brief: The human readable name of the pipeline within a CI/CD system.

content.name: cicd.pipeline.run.id
content.brief: The unique identifier of a pipeline run within a CI/CD system.

content.name: cicd.pipeline.run.state
content.brief: The pipeline run goes through these states during its lifecycle.

content.name: cicd.pipeline.task.name
content.brief: The human readable name of a task within a pipeline. Task here most closely aligns with a [computing process](https://wikipedia.org/wiki/Pipeline_(computing)) in a pipeline. Other terms for tasks include commands, steps, and procedures.

content.name: cicd.pipeline.task.run.id
content.brief: The unique identifier of a task run within a pipeline.

content.name: cicd.pipeline.task.run.url.full
content.brief: The [URL](https://wikipedia.org/wiki/URL) of the pipeline run providing the complete address in order to locate and identify the pipeline run.

content.name: cicd.pipeline.task.type
content.brief: The type of the task within a pipeline.

content.name: cicd.pipeline.result
content.brief: The result of a pipeline run.

content.name: cicd.worker.state
content.brief: The state of a CICD worker / agent.

content.name: cicd.system.component
content.brief: The name of a component of the CICD system.

content.name: http.request.body.size
content.brief: The size of the request payload body in bytes. This is the number of bytes transferred excluding headers and is often, but not always, present as the [Content-Length](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9110.html#field.content-length) header. For requests using transport encoding, this should be the compressed size.

content.name: http.request.header
content.brief: HTTP request headers, `<key>` being the normalized HTTP Header name (lowercase), the value being the header values.

content.name: http.request.method
content.brief: HTTP request method.

content.name: http.request.method_original
content.brief: Original HTTP method sent by the client in the request line.

content.name: http.request.resend_count
content.brief: The ordinal number of request resending attempt (for any reason, including redirects).

content.name: http.request.size
content.brief: The total size of the request in bytes. This should be the total number of bytes sent over the wire, including the request line (HTTP/1.1), framing (HTTP/2 and HTTP/3), headers, and request body if any.

content.name: http.response.body.size
content.brief: The size of the response payload body in bytes. This is the number of bytes transferred excluding headers and is often, but not always, present as the [Content-Length](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9110.html#field.content-length) header. For requests using transport encoding, this should be the compressed size.

content.name: http.response.header
content.brief: HTTP response headers, `<key>` being the normalized HTTP Header name (lowercase), the value being the header values.

content.name: http.response.size
content.brief: The total size of the response in bytes. This should be the total number of bytes sent over the wire, including the status line (HTTP/1.1), framing (HTTP/2 and HTTP/3), headers, and response body and trailers if any.

content.name: http.response.status_code
content.brief: [HTTP response status code](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7231#section-6).

content.name: http.route
content.brief: The matched route, that is, the path template in the format used by the respective server framework.

content.name: http.connection.state
content.brief: State of the HTTP connection in the HTTP connection pool.

content.name: security_rule.category
content.brief: A categorization value keyword used by the entity using the rule for detection of this event

content.name: security_rule.description
content.brief: The description of the rule generating the event.
examples: Block requests to public DNS over HTTPS / TLS protocols

content.name: security_rule.license
content.brief: Name of the license under which the rule used to generate this event is made available.

content.name: security_rule.name
content.brief: The name of the rule or signature generating the event.

content.name: security_rule.reference
content.brief: Reference URL to additional information about the rule used to generate this event.

content.name: security_rule.ruleset.name
content.brief: Name of the ruleset, policy, group, or parent category in which the rule used to generate this event is a member.

content.name: security_rule.uuid
content.brief: A rule ID that is unique within the scope of a set or group of agents, observers, or other entities using the rule for detection of this event.

content.name: security_rule.version
content.brief: The version / revision of the rule being used for analysis.

content.name: tls.cipher
content.brief: String indicating the [cipher](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5246#appendix-A.5) used during the current connection.

content.name: tls.client.certificate
content.brief: PEM-encoded stand-alone certificate offered by the client. This is usually mutually-exclusive of `client.certificate_chain` since this value also exists in that list.

content.name: tls.client.certificate_chain
content.brief: Array of PEM-encoded certificates that make up the certificate chain offered by the client. This is usually mutually-exclusive of `client.certificate` since that value should be the first certificate in the chain.

content.name: tls.client.hash.md5
content.brief: Certificate fingerprint using the MD5 digest of DER-encoded version of certificate offered by the client. For consistency with other hash values, this value should be formatted as an uppercase hash.

content.name: tls.client.hash.sha1
content.brief: Certificate fingerprint using the SHA1 digest of DER-encoded version of certificate offered by the client. For consistency with other hash values, this value should be formatted as an uppercase hash.

content.name: tls.client.hash.sha256
content.brief: Certificate fingerprint using the SHA256 digest of DER-encoded version of certificate offered by the client. For consistency with other hash values, this value should be formatted as an uppercase hash.

content.name: tls.client.issuer
content.brief: Distinguished name of [subject](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5280#section-4.1.2.6) of the issuer of the x.509 certificate presented by the client.
examples: CN=Example Root CA, OU=Infrastructure Team, DC=example, DC=com

content.name: tls.client.ja3
content.brief: A hash that identifies clients based on how they perform an SSL/TLS handshake.

content.name: tls.client.not_after
content.brief: Date/Time indicating when client certificate is no longer considered valid.

content.name: tls.client.not_before
content.brief: Date/Time indicating when client certificate is first considered valid.

content.name: tls.client.subject
content.brief: Distinguished name of subject of the x.509 certificate presented by the client.

content.name: tls.client.supported_ciphers
content.brief: Array of ciphers offered by the client during the client hello.

content.name: tls.curve
content.brief: String indicating the curve used for the given cipher, when applicable

content.name: tls.established
content.brief: Boolean flag indicating if the TLS negotiation was successful and transitioned to an encrypted tunnel.

content.name: tls.next_protocol
content.brief: String indicating the protocol being tunneled. Per the values in the [IANA registry](https://www.iana.org/assignments/tls-extensiontype-values/tls-extensiontype-values.xhtml#alpn-protocol-ids), this string should be lower case.

content.name: tls.protocol.name
content.brief: Normalized lowercase protocol name parsed from original string of the negotiated [SSL/TLS protocol version](https://www.openssl.org/docs/man1.1.1/man3/SSL_get_version.html#RETURN-VALUES)

content.name: tls.protocol.version
content.brief: Numeric part of the version parsed from the original string of the negotiated [SSL/TLS protocol version](https://www.openssl.org/docs/man1.1.1/man3/SSL_get_version.html#RETURN-VALUES)

content.name: tls.resumed
content.brief: Boolean flag indicating if this TLS connection was resumed from an existing TLS negotiation.

content.name: tls.server.certificate
content.brief: PEM-encoded stand-alone certificate offered by the server. This is usually mutually-exclusive of `server.certificate_chain` since this value also exists in that list.

content.name: tls.server.certificate_chain
content.brief: Array of PEM-encoded certificates that make up the certificate chain offered by the server. This is usually mutually-exclusive of `server.certificate` since that value should be the first certificate in the chain.

content.name: tls.server.hash.md5
content.brief: Certificate fingerprint using the MD5 digest of DER-encoded version of certificate offered by the server. For consistency with other hash values, this value should be formatted as an uppercase hash.

content.name: tls.server.hash.sha1
content.brief: Certificate fingerprint using the SHA1 digest of DER-encoded version of certificate offered by the server. For consistency with other hash values, this value should be formatted as an uppercase hash.

content.name: tls.server.hash.sha256
content.brief: Certificate fingerprint using the SHA256 digest of DER-encoded version of certificate offered by the server. For consistency with other hash values, this value should be formatted as an uppercase hash.

content.name: tls.server.issuer
content.brief: Distinguished name of [subject](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5280#section-4.1.2.6) of the issuer of the x.509 certificate presented by the client.
examples: CN=Example Root CA, OU=Infrastructure Team, DC=example, DC=com

content.name: tls.server.ja3s
content.brief: A hash that identifies servers based on how they perform an SSL/TLS handshake.

content.name: tls.server.not_after
content.brief: Date/Time indicating when server certificate is no longer considered valid.

content.name: tls.server.not_before
content.brief: Date/Time indicating when server certificate is first considered valid.

content.name: tls.server.subject
content.brief: Distinguished name of subject of the x.509 certificate presented by the server.

content.name: cloudevents.event_id
content.brief: The [event_id](https://github.com/cloudevents/spec/blob/v1.0.2/cloudevents/spec.md#id) uniquely identifies the event.

content.name: cloudevents.event_source
content.brief: The [source](https://github.com/cloudevents/spec/blob/v1.0.2/cloudevents/spec.md#source-1) identifies the context in which an event happened.

content.name: cloudevents.event_spec_version
content.brief: The [version of the CloudEvents specification](https://github.com/cloudevents/spec/blob/v1.0.2/cloudevents/spec.md#specversion) which the event uses.

content.name: cloudevents.event_type
content.brief: The [event_type](https://github.com/cloudevents/spec/blob/v1.0.2/cloudevents/spec.md#type) contains a value describing the type of event related to the originating occurrence.

content.name: cloudevents.event_subject
content.brief: The [subject](https://github.com/cloudevents/spec/blob/v1.0.2/cloudevents/spec.md#subject) of the event in the context of the event producer (identified by source).

content.name: user.email
content.brief: User email address.

content.name: user.full_name
content.brief: User's full name

content.name: user.hash
content.brief: Unique user hash to correlate information for a user in anonymized form.

content.name: user.id
content.brief: Unique identifier of the user.

content.name: user.name
content.brief: Short name or login/username of the user.

content.name: user.roles
content.brief: Array of user roles at the time of the event.

content.name: browser.brands
content.brief: Array of brand name and version separated by a space

content.name: browser.platform
content.brief: The platform on which the browser is running

content.name: browser.mobile
content.brief: A boolean that is true if the browser is running on a mobile device

content.name: browser.language
content.brief: Preferred language of the user using the browser

content.name: faas.name
content.brief: The name of the single function that this runtime instance executes.

content.name: faas.version
content.brief: The immutable version of the function being executed.

content.name: faas.instance
content.brief: The execution environment ID as a string, that will be potentially reused for other invocations to the same function/function version.

content.name: faas.max_memory
content.brief: The amount of memory available to the serverless function converted to Bytes.

content.name: faas.trigger
content.brief: Type of the trigger which caused this function invocation.

content.name: faas.invoked_name
content.brief: The name of the invoked function.

content.name: faas.invoked_provider
content.brief: The cloud provider of the invoked function.

content.name: faas.invoked_region
content.brief: The cloud region of the invoked function.

content.name: faas.invocation_id
content.brief: The invocation ID of the current function invocation.

content.name: faas.time
content.brief: A string containing the function invocation time in the [ISO 8601](https://www.iso.org/iso-8601-date-and-time-format.html) format expressed in [UTC](https://www.w3.org/TR/NOTE-datetime).

content.name: faas.cron
content.brief: A string containing the schedule period as [Cron Expression](https://docs.oracle.com/cd/E12058_01/doc/doc.1014/e12030/cron_expressions.htm).

content.name: faas.coldstart
content.brief: A boolean that is true if the serverless function is executed for the first time (aka cold-start).

content.name: faas.document.collection
content.brief: The name of the source on which the triggering operation was performed. For example, in Cloud Storage or S3 corresponds to the bucket name, and in Cosmos DB to the database name.

content.name: faas.document.operation
content.brief: Describes the type of the operation that was performed on the data.

content.name: faas.document.time
content.brief: A string containing the time when the data was accessed in the [ISO 8601](https://www.iso.org/iso-8601-date-and-time-format.html) format expressed in [UTC](https://www.w3.org/TR/NOTE-datetime).

content.name: faas.document.name
content.brief: The document name/table subjected to the operation. For example, in Cloud Storage or S3 is the name of the file, and in Cosmos DB the table name.

content.name: elasticsearch.node.name
content.brief: Represents the human-readable identifier of the node/instance to which a request was routed.

content.name: process.pid
content.brief: Process identifier (PID).

content.name: process.parent_pid
content.brief: Parent Process identifier (PPID).

content.name: process.vpid
content.brief: Virtual process identifier.

content.name: process.session_leader.pid
content.brief: The PID of the process's session leader. This is also the session ID (SID) of the process.

content.name: process.group_leader.pid
content.brief: The PID of the process's group leader. This is also the process group ID (PGID) of the process.

content.name: process.executable.build_id.gnu
content.brief: The GNU build ID as found in the `.note.gnu.build-id` ELF section (hex string).

content.name: process.executable.build_id.go
content.brief: The Go build ID as retrieved by `go tool buildid <go executable>`.

content.name: process.executable.build_id.htlhash
content.brief: Profiling specific build ID for executables. See the OTel specification for Profiles for more information.

content.name: process.executable.name
content.brief: The name of the process executable. On Linux based systems, can be set to the `Name` in `proc/[pid]/status`. On Windows, can be set to the base name of `GetProcessImageFileNameW`.

content.name: process.executable.path
content.brief: The full path to the process executable. On Linux based systems, can be set to the target of `proc/[pid]/exe`. On Windows, can be set to the result of `GetProcessImageFileNameW`.

content.name: process.command
content.brief: The command used to launch the process (i.e. the command name). On Linux based systems, can be set to the zeroth string in `proc/[pid]/cmdline`. On Windows, can be set to the first parameter extracted from `GetCommandLineW`.

content.name: process.command_line
content.brief: The full command used to launch the process as a single string representing the full command. On Windows, can be set to the result of `GetCommandLineW`. Do not set this if you have to assemble it just for monitoring; use `process.command_args` instead.

content.name: process.command_args
content.brief: All the command arguments (including the command/executable itself) as received by the process. On Linux-based systems (and some other Unixoid systems supporting procfs), can be set according to the list of null-delimited strings extracted from `proc/[pid]/cmdline`. For libc-based executables, this would be the full argv vector passed to `main`.

content.name: process.args_count
content.brief: Length of the process.command_args array

content.name: process.owner
content.brief: The username of the user that owns the process.

content.name: process.user.id
content.brief: The effective user ID (EUID) of the process.

content.name: process.user.name
content.brief: The username of the effective user of the process.

content.name: process.real_user.id
content.brief: The real user ID (RUID) of the process.

content.name: process.real_user.name
content.brief: The username of the real user of the process.

content.name: process.saved_user.id
content.brief: The saved user ID (SUID) of the process.

content.name: process.saved_user.name
content.brief: The username of the saved user.

content.name: process.runtime.name
content.brief: The name of the runtime of this process.

content.name: process.runtime.version
content.brief: The version of the runtime of this process, as returned by the runtime without modification.

content.name: process.runtime.description
content.brief: An additional description about the runtime of the process, for example a specific vendor customization of the runtime environment.
content.examples: Eclipse OpenJ9 Eclipse OpenJ9 VM openj9-0.21.0

content.name: process.title
content.brief: Process title (proctitle)

content.name: process.creation.time
content.brief: The date and time the process was created, in ISO 8601 format.

content.name: process.exit.time
content.brief: The date and time the process exited, in ISO 8601 format.

content.name: process.exit.code
content.brief: The exit code of the process.

content.name: process.interactive
content.brief: Whether the process is connected to an interactive shell.

content.name: process.working_directory
content.brief: The working directory of the process.

content.name: process.context_switch_type
content.brief: Specifies whether the context switches for this data point were voluntary or involuntary.

content.name: process.paging.fault_type
content.brief: The type of page fault for this data point. Type `major` is for major/hard page faults, and `minor` is for minor/soft page faults.

content.name: exception.type
content.brief: The type of the exception (its fully-qualified class name, if applicable). The dynamic type of the exception should be preferred over the static type in languages that support it.

content.name: exception.message
content.brief: The exception message.
examples: Can't convert 'int' object to str implicitly

content.name: exception.stacktrace
content.brief: A stacktrace as a string in the natural representation for the language runtime. The representation is to be determined and documented by each language SIG.
content.examples:
Exception in thread "main" java.lang.RuntimeException: Test exception
 at com.example.GenerateTrace.methodB(GenerateTrace.java:13)
 at com.example.GenerateTrace.methodA(GenerateTrace.java:9)
 at com.example.GenerateTrace.main(GenerateTrace.java:5)

content.name: webengine.name
content.brief: The name of the web engine.

content.name: webengine.version
content.brief: The version of the web engine.

content.name: webengine.description
content.brief: Additional description of the web engine (e.g. detailed version and edition information).

content.name: az.service_request_id
content.brief: The unique identifier of the service request. It's generated by the Azure service and returned with the response.

content.name: az.namespace
content.brief: [Azure Resource Provider Namespace](https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/azure-resource-manager/management/azure-services-resource-providers) as recognized by the client.

content.name: azure.client.id
content.brief: The unique identifier of the client instance.

content.name: hw.id
content.brief: An identifier for the hardware component, unique within the monitored host

content.name: hw.name
content.brief: An easily-recognizable name for the hardware component

content.name: hw.parent
content.brief: Unique identifier of the parent component (typically the `hw.id` attribute of the enclosure, or disk controller)

content.name: hw.type
content.brief: Type of the component

content.name: hw.state
content.brief: The current state of the component

content.name: device.id
content.brief: A unique identifier representing the device

content.name: device.manufacturer
content.brief: The name of the device manufacturer

content.name: device.model.identifier
content.brief: The model identifier for the device

content.name: device.model.name
content.brief: The marketing name for the device model

content.name: url.domain
content.brief: Domain extracted from the `url.full`, such as "opentelemetry.io".

content.name: url.extension
content.brief: The file extension extracted from the `url.full`, excluding the leading dot.

content.name: url.fragment
content.brief: The [URI fragment](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3986#section-3.5) component

content.name: url.full
content.brief: Absolute URL describing a network resource according to [RFC3986](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3986)

content.name: url.original
content.brief: Unmodified original URL as seen in the event source.

content.name: url.path
content.brief: The [URI path](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3986#section-3.3) component

content.name: url.port
content.brief: Port extracted from the `url.full`

content.name: url.query
content.brief: The [URI query](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3986#section-3.4) component

content.name: url.registered_domain
content.brief: The highest registered url domain, stripped of the subdomain.

content.name: url.scheme
content.brief: The [URI scheme](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3986#section-3.1) component identifying the used protocol.

content.name: url.subdomain
content.brief: The subdomain portion of a fully qualified domain name includes all of the names except the host name under the registered_domain. In a partially qualified domain, or if the qualification level of the full name cannot be determined, subdomain contains all of the names below the registered domain.

content.name: url.template
content.brief: The low-cardinality template of an [absolute path reference](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3986#section-4.2).

content.name: url.top_level_domain
content.brief: The effective top level domain (eTLD), also known as the domain suffix, is the last part of the domain name. For example, the top level domain for example.com is `com`.

content.name: messaging.batch.message_count
content.brief: The number of messages sent, received, or processed in the scope of the batching operation.

content.name: messaging.client.id
content.brief: A unique identifier for the client that consumes or produces a message.

content.name: messaging.consumer.group.name
content.brief: The name of the consumer group with which a consumer is associated.

content.name: messaging.destination.name
content.brief: The message destination name

content.name: messaging.destination.subscription.name

content.name: messaging.destination.anonymous
content.brief: A boolean that is true if the message destination is anonymous (could be unnamed or have auto-generated name).

content.name: messaging.destination.temporary
content.brief: A boolean that is true if the message destination is temporary and might not exist anymore after messages are processed.

content.name: messaging.destination.partition.id

content.name: messaging.message.body.size
content.brief: The size of the message body in bytes.

content.name: messaging.operation.type
content.brief: A string identifying the type of the messaging operation.

content.name: messaging.operation.name
content.brief: The system-specific name of the messaging operation.
